Definitions
SSH - Secured shell
ufw - uncomplicated firewall
SSHD - Secured shell daemon
Daemon - A proccess that runes in the background
IP - Internet protocol
SSH into remote server - The user you used to log in @ the name of your device or IP address of remote server


Procedure steps
[Describe each step of the procedure and mention any known hazards or difficulties.]
Step 1: update the package manager - sudo apt udpate
Step 2: install the firewall package onto the server - sudo apt install ufw -y
Step 3: enable the firewall - sudo ufw enable
Step 4: Enable the sshd - sudo systemctl enable ssh --now
Step 5: allow ssh to be allowed pass the firewall - sudo ufw allow ssh
Step 6: Confirm your IP address is correct an able to ping gateway address - ip a, ip r and ping 
Step 7: Try to SSH into the remote server - ssh username@Device name/ IP address of device
Step 8: Create SSH keys on your local machine - ssh-keygen
Step 9: copy the SSH keys into your remote server - ssh-copy-id username@Device name/IP address of device

Expected Results:
You should be able to ssh into the remote server using the username and device name/IP address of the device without having to type in any passwords.
Verification:
After typing in the user and device you want to remotely configure you can see the user and device that you wanted to remote into.
Troubleshooting:
check if the firewall is online - sudo ufw status verbose or sudo systemctl status ufw
reload firewall refresh changes if needed - sudo ufw reload
Check if the sshd is online - sudo systemctl status ssh or sudo systemctl status sshd
Network Configuration commands - nmcli connection show, nmcli device status, sudo systemctl restart NetworkManager
Security Considerations:
Check the open ports on the Linux server - sudo ss -tupln

